    "teacher_markdown": "1. When a negative number is entered for the price, the program accepts the input and sets the price as a negative. Unless a store wants to give away money along with merchandise, then the program should be altered to not accept `newPrice` <= 0.0\r\n\r\n2. Another example utilizing an `if-else` control structure can be seen below:\r\n\r\n```\r\n    if (newPrice > 0){\r\n      price = newPrice;\r\n      System.out.println(\"Price updated to $\" + price);\r\n    } else {\r\n      System.out.println(\"This is an invalid price, please try again.\");\r\n    }\r\n```\r\n3. The program utilizes a `while` loop which keeps prompting the user to modify the size or the price as long as the input is not zero. There are two conditional statements within this loop that check for either a 1 or a 2 as input and then run the corresponding methods (`setSize` & `setPrice` respectively). Therefore, if a user enters a value that is not 0, 1, or 2, the program will loop and reprompt the user to input their choice.\r\n\r\n4. In order to account for invalid input, the program structure could be modified using an `if-else if-else` structure as seen below:\r\n```\r\n      if (choice == 1) {\r\n        System.out.print(\"Enter the new size: \");\r\n        String size = input.nextLine();\r\n        setSize(size);\r\n      } else if (choice == 2) {\r\n        System.out.print(\"Enter the new price: \");\r\n        double price = input.nextDouble();\r\n        setPrice(price);\r\n      } else {\r\n        System.out.println(\"This choice is invalid. Please try again\");\r\n      }\r\n````",
